# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bete-ombro
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] The 100-ball game has two teams each having a single innings, which is restricted to a maximum of 100 balls, and the match lasts approximately two and a half hours, shorter than the Twenty20 format.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] Before the launch of the professional The Hundred competition in July 2021, the 100-ball format was trialled in several amateur local leagues across England.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] The new 100-ball format was born out of a proposal by the England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB) in 2016 to launch a new franchise cricket competition, similar to the Indian Premier League.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] At first it was expected that the competition would use the existing Twenty20 format.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] Following discussions involving the ECB's marketing team, clubs were instead told in April 2018 that the competition would use an entirely new form of cricket designed to be simpler to follow and shorter to fit television schedules.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] The more detailed proposal was presented by the ECB to the chair and chief executives of the first-class counties and the MCC on 19 April 2018, and was unanimously supported by the board of the new competition.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] At first it was proposed that each innings would involve 15 six-ball overs and a final 10-ball over.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] In February 2019, the ECB announced tweaks to the proposed rules of 100-ball cricket.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] The competition will instead contain 10 ten-ball overs, i.e. a change of ends after ten balls.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] A bowler will be delivering five or 10 consecutive balls.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] A bowler would deliver a maximum of 20 balls per innings.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] Power-play conditions were also announced.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] Trial events using the format took place at The Purchasers annual cricket festival at Belmont House in Kent, and club level in England.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] In November 2018, the Warwickshire Cricket Board and Warwickshire County Cricket Club launched the 100-ball format club level tournament, which is designed to revitalise Sunday cricket at clubs across the Midlands.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] Called the Warwickshire Sunday Smash, the 16 team tournament is split into three divisions, with each side playing each team both home and away, throughout June and July.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] The teams include Solihull Blossomfield Cricket Club, Knowle & Dorridge, Sutton Coldfield, Bedworth, Alcester & Ragley, Stratford upon Avon, Water Orton, Four Oaks Saints, Moseley Ashfield and Aston Manor, who are all members of the Midlands Club Cricket Conference.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] The winners of each league and the best second place progressing to the Semi-Finals Day.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] The Finals Day took place on 1 September 2019 at Edgbaston.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] Stratford Upon Avon beat Knowle & Dorridge to win the first 100-ball competition in the UK.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] Shropshire County Cricket Club introduced the Swancote Energy Smash, which began in June 2019.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] It is a six-team tournament that has been divided into two groups, with games being played every Thursday night.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] The winners of each group is due to play in the inaugural final in early September 2019.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] The six teams are Shifnal, Claverley, Worfield, Bridgnorth, Chelmarsh and Wombourne.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] In May 2021 Shropshire Cricket league launched two 100-ball knock out competitions, known as the Aaron's 100 and Aaron's Premier 100, involving 53 teams from across Shropshire and mid-Wales.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] Cricket Wales launched the Cricket Wales U19’s 100 Ball Cup for under 19 year olds.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] It started on 25 June 2021 and is due to end with the final on 13 August 2021 at Ynystawe Cricket Club.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] The Cricket Paper National Girls U18 100 Ball Cup was established by Shrewsbury School.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] Originally known as the Shrewsbury School Girls U18 T20 in 2019, it is now a 100-ball cricket competition.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] The first professional competition using the 100-ball format was The Hundred in July 2021.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] The Hundred involves eight men's and women's teams across England and Wales.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] The first professional match using the new format involved the women's teams of the Oval Invincibles and Manchester Originals who played each other at The Oval in London on 21 July 2021.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] The Africa Cricket Association plans to hold an annual 100-ball competition to further boost the game within the continent.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] 100-ball cricket is a form of limited overs cricket, played by two teams each playing a single innings made up of 100 balls.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] English journalist George Dobell wrote in 2018 that proposals for the new format outlined by the ECB were nothing more than a further step towards "fast-food cricket", whereas others support the proposals.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] England's then Test captain, Joe Root, welcomed the ECB's plans for its new-team format in 2020.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] According to Root, it will attract a completely new audience.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] ODI and T20 captain, Eoin Morgan, had a similar opinion about this format.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] Former T20 captain Stuart Broad said he was hugely optimistic about the new format.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] Michael Vaughan also echoed Broad and stated that it will be a more appealing concept to broadcasters.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] Michael Atherton shared that a T20 match was originally to be completed in a 3-hour window and this can be achieved with the proposed format.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] New Zealand all-rounder Jimmy Neesham was bemused on this move, asking why the England and Wales Cricket Board is trying something different when the current format is already so successful.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] Current limited overs specialists Dawid Malan and Mark Wood shared that in spite of the new format, T20s will still remain as the preference.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] Former MCC chief Keith Bradshaw called the 100-ball tournament an innovation for innovation's sake, reasoning that the main reason behind this thought process is that the ECB could not exploit the T20 boom.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] The England and Wales Professional Cricketers' Association shared that, overall, players were open to this new idea.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] Meanwhile, Cricket Australia has no plans to tinker with its existing Big Bash League.
[src:bete-ombro/100-ball-cricket] It also shared a concern that the introduction of shorter formats is further ignoring Test cricket.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] Backyard cricket has connections to the pastimes of Australian, South African and New Zealand and English children who frequently lived on properties with large backyards, providing the facility to play this informal game of sport often with friends, family and neighbors.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] In South Asia, backyard cricket is very popular.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] Though loosely based upon the game of cricket, many aspects are improvised: the playing ground, the rules, the teams, and the equipment.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] Quite often there are no teams at all; the players take turns at batting and there is often no emphasis on actually scoring runs.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] Games with relatively few players typically forgo the teams and innings format of professional cricket, opting instead for a batters-vs-everyone format.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] Garden/backyard cricket in South Africa and Australia is considered by many to be the pinnacle event of social and sporting excellence in the summer period.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] Many games are paired with a barbecue which often has a carnival atmosphere.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] It is historically very popular on Australia Day.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] As a generally informal contest, the rules are flexible but usually agreed upon by the players prior to playing it.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] Below are listed some of the most common rules.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] Backyard cricket allows for rules to be changed, and the rules being played by will depend on the context and physical environment of the game, and the traditions and experience of the players.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] If the game is not played individually, the person who owns the bat and ball may choose to bat first.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] Play on an actual beach can be achieved either by using the flat strip of hard-packed sand along the surf line as the pitch, or by only "bowling" gentle full tosses to avoid the problem of the ball not bouncing off loose sand.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] If there are no true stumps available, then a bin, deckchair, boogie board or cool box may be used.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] Tennis balls are often used in place of cricket balls as they float in the water and don't get bogged in the sand as easily.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] In beach cricket the creases and the boundary are normally drawn in the sand in a line which extends well past the side of the agreed pitch to prevent them becoming obliterated in the first over.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] The batters will frequently redraw the line.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] Sometimes, play is shifted along the beach to a new pitch as the packed sand of the original pitch is turned up, thus reducing the standard of or even completely disabling bowling.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] The tide plays a big part in the standard of the pitch in beach cricket.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] During low tide, the pitch tends to be on the semi-wet sand, and is deemed superior than cricket played in high tide (when the pitch is on dryer, looser sand).
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] In particularly long matches, the play will shift up and down the beach depending on the tide.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] A major element of contemporary street cricket is the use of a tennis ball; in Pakistan, tennis balls began to be covered in tape in the late 20th century and turned into a "tape ball".
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] Tape ball cricket is played to the greatest extent in Pakistan, where it likely originated.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] Several street variants of cricket exist in Latin America, such as bete-ombro and plaquita.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] In nearby Suriname, there is a game called "bat-en-bal" which is likely derived from cricket; in bat-en-bal, one end of the pitch has a set of stumps.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] In March 2024, the first season of the Indian Street Premier League (ISPL) took place, which featured several elements of Indian street cricket such as the use of a tennis ball.
[src:bete-ombro/backyard-cricket] The ISPL's goal is to prioritize the advancement of poorer cricket players and support the growth of tennis ball cricket.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The initial objective of the batting team is to have a player reach first base safely; this occurs either when the batter hits the ball and reaches first base before an opponent retrieves the ball and touches the base, or when the pitcher persists in throwing the ball out of the batter's reach.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Players on the batting team who reach first base without being called "out" can attempt to advance to subsequent bases as a runner, either immediately or during teammates' turns batting.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The fielding team tries to prevent runs by using the ball to get batters or runners "out", which forces them out of the field of play.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The pitcher can get the batter out by throwing three pitches which result in strikes, while fielders can get the batter out by catching a batted ball before it touches the ground, and can get a runner out by tagging them with the ball while the runner is not touching a base.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The opposing teams switch back and forth between batting and fielding; the batting team's turn to bat is over once the fielding team records three outs.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] One turn batting for each team constitutes an inning.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A game is usually composed of nine innings, and the team with the greater number of runs at the end of the game wins.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Most games end after the ninth inning, but if scores are tied at that point, extra innings are usually played.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Baseball has no game clock, though some competitions feature pace-of-play regulations such as a pitch clock to shorten game time.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Baseball evolved from older bat-and-ball games already being played in England by the mid-18th century.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] This game was brought by immigrants to North America, where the modern version developed.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In addition to North America, baseball spread throughout the rest of the Americas and the Asia–Pacific in the 19th and 20th centuries, and is now considered the most popular sport in parts of Central and South America, the Caribbean, and East Asia, particularly in Japan, South Korea, and Taiwan.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In Major League Baseball (MLB), the highest level of professional baseball in the United States and Canada, teams are divided into the National League (NL) and American League (AL), each with three divisions: East, West, and Central.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The MLB champion is determined by playoffs that culminate in the World Series.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The top level of play is similarly split in Japan between the Central and Pacific Leagues and in Cuba between the West League and East League.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The World Baseball Classic, organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation, is the major international competition of the sport and attracts the top national teams from around the world.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Baseball was played at the Olympic Games from 1992 to 2008, and was reinstated on a one-off basis in 2020.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A baseball game is played between two teams, each composed of nine players, that take turns playing offense (batting and baserunning) and defense (pitching and fielding).
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A pair of turns, one at bat and one in the field, by each team constitutes an inning.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A game consists of nine innings (seven innings at the high school level and in doubleheaders in college and Minor League Baseball; and six innings at the Little League level).
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] One team—customarily the visiting team—bats in the top, or first half, of every inning.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The other team—customarily the home team—bats in the bottom, or second half, of every inning.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The goal of the game is to score more points (runs) than the other team.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The players on the team at bat attempt to score runs by touching all four bases, in order, set at the corners of the square-shaped baseball diamond.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A player bats at home plate and must attempt to safely reach a base before proceeding, counterclockwise, from first base, to second base, third base, and back home to score a run.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The team in the field attempts to prevent runs from scoring by recording outs, which remove opposing players from offensive action until their next turn at bat comes up again.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] When three outs are recorded, the teams switch roles for the next half-inning.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] If the score of the game is tied after nine innings, extra innings are played to resolve the contest.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Many amateur games, particularly unorganized ones, involve different numbers of players and innings.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The game is played on a field whose primary boundaries, the foul lines, extend forward from home plate at 45-degree angles.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The 90-degree area within the foul lines is referred to as fair territory; the 270-degree area outside them is foul territory.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The part of the field enclosed by the bases and several yards beyond them is the infield; the area farther beyond the infield is the outfield.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In the middle of the infield is a raised pitcher's mound, with a rectangular rubber plate (the rubber) at its center.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The outer boundary of the outfield is typically demarcated by a raised fence, which may be of any material and height.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The fair territory between home plate and the outfield boundary is baseball's field of play, though significant events can take place in foul territory, as well.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Protective helmets are also standard equipment for all batters.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] At the beginning of each half-inning, the nine players of the fielding team arrange themselves around the field.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] One of them, the pitcher, stands on the pitcher's mound.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The pitcher begins the pitching delivery with one foot on the rubber, pushing off it to gain velocity when throwing toward home plate.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Another fielding team player, the catcher, squats on the far side of home plate, facing the pitcher.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The rest of the fielding team faces home plate, typically arranged as four infielders—who set up along or within a few yards outside the imaginary lines (basepaths) between first, second, and third base—and three outfielders.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In the standard arrangement, there is a first baseman positioned several steps to the left of first base, a second baseman to the right of second base, a shortstop to the left of second base, and a third baseman to the right of third base.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The basic outfield positions are left fielder, center fielder, and right fielder.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] With the exception of the catcher, all fielders are required to be in fair territory when the pitch is delivered.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A neutral umpire sets up behind the catcher.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Other umpires will be distributed around the field as well.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Play starts with a member of the batting team, the batter, standing in either of the two batter's boxes next to home plate, holding a bat.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The batter waits for the pitcher to throw a pitch (the ball) toward home plate, and attempts to hit the ball with the bat.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The catcher catches pitches that the batter does not hit—as a result of either electing not to swing or failing to connect—and returns them to the pitcher.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A batter who hits the ball into the field of play must drop the bat and begin running toward first base, at which point the player is referred to as a *runner* (or, until the play is over, a *batter-runner*).
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A batter-runner who reaches first base without being put out is said to be *safe* and is on base.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A batter-runner may choose to remain at first base or attempt to advance to second base or even beyond—however far the player believes can be reached safely.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base despite proper play by the fielders has recorded a hit.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A player who reaches first base safely on a hit is credited with a single.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] If a player makes it to second base safely as a direct result of a hit, it is a double; third base, a triple.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air within the foul lines over the entire outfield (and outfield fence, if there is one), or if the batter-runner otherwise safely circles all the bases, it is a home run: the batter and any runners on base may all freely circle the bases, each scoring a run.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] This is the most desirable result for the batter.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The ultimate and most desirable result possible for a batter would be to hit a home run while all three bases are occupied or "loaded", thus scoring four runs on a single hit.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base due to a fielding mistake is not credited with a hit—instead, the responsible fielder is charged with an error.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Any runners already on base may attempt to advance on batted balls that land, or contact the ground, in fair territory, before or after the ball lands.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A runner on first base *must* attempt to advance if a ball lands in play, as only one runner may occupy a base at any given time; the same applies for other runners if they are on a base that a teammate is forced to advance to.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] If a ball hit into play rolls foul before passing through the infield, it becomes dead and any runners must return to the base they occupied when the play began.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air and caught before it lands, the batter has flied out and any runners on base may attempt to advance only if they tag up (contact the base they occupied when the play began, as or after the ball is caught).
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Runners may also attempt to advance to the next base while the pitcher is in the process of delivering the ball to home plate; a successful effort is a stolen base.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A pitch that is not hit into the field of play is called either a strike or a ball.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A batter against whom three strikes are recorded strikes out.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A batter against whom four balls are recorded is awarded a base on balls or walk, a free advance to first base.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] While the team at bat is trying to score runs, the team in the field is attempting to record outs.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In addition to the strikeout and flyout, common ways a member of the batting team may be put out include the ground out, force out, and tag out.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] These occur either when a runner is forced to advance to a base, and a fielder with possession of the ball reaches that base before the runner does, or the runner is touched by the ball, held in a fielder's hand, while not on a base.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] (The batter-runner is always forced to advance to first base, and any other runners must advance to the next base if a teammate is forced to advance to their base.) It is possible to record two outs in the course of the same play.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Three outs in one play, a triple play, is possible, though rare.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Players put out or retired must leave the field, returning to their team's dugout or bench.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A runner may be stranded on base when a third out is recorded against another player on the team.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Stranded runners do not benefit the team in its next turn at bat as every half-inning begins with the bases empty.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] An individual player's turn batting or plate appearance is complete when the player reaches base, hits a home run, makes an out, or hits a ball that results in the team's third out, even if it is recorded against a teammate.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] On rare occasions, a batter may be at the plate when, without the batter's hitting the ball, a third out is recorded against a teammate—for instance, a runner getting caught stealing (tagged out attempting to steal a base).
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A batter with this sort of incomplete plate appearance starts off the team's next turn batting; any balls or strikes recorded against the batter the previous inning are erased.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A runner may circle the bases only once per plate appearance and thus can score at most a single run per batting turn.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Once a player has completed a plate appearance, that player may not bat again until the eight other members of the player's team have all taken their turn at bat in the batting order.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The batting order is set before the game begins, and may not be altered except for substitutions.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Once a player has been removed for a substitute, that player may not reenter the game.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Children's games often have more lenient rules, such as Little League rules, which allow players to be substituted back into the same game.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] If the designated hitter (DH) rule is in effect, each team has a tenth player whose sole responsibility is to bat (and run).
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The DH takes the place of another player—almost invariably the pitcher—in the batting order, but does not field.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Thus, even with the DH, each team still has a batting order of nine players and a fielding arrangement of nine players.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The number of players on a baseball roster, or *squad*, varies by league and by the level of organized play.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A Major League Baseball (MLB) team has a roster of 26 players with specific roles.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Most baseball leagues worldwide have the DH rule, including MLB, Japan's Pacific League, and Caribbean professional leagues, along with major American amateur organizations.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The Central League in Japan does not have the rule and high-level minor league clubs connected to National League teams are not required to field a DH.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In leagues that apply the designated hitter rule, a typical team has nine offensive regulars (including the DH), five starting pitchers, seven or eight relievers, a backup catcher, and two or three other reserve players.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The manager, or head coach, oversees the team's major strategic decisions, such as establishing the starting rotation, setting the lineup, or batting order, before each game, and making substitutions during games—in particular, bringing in relief pitchers.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Managers are typically assisted by two or more coaches; they may have specialized responsibilities, such as working with players on hitting, fielding, pitching, or strength and conditioning.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] At most levels of organized play, two coaches are stationed on the field when the team is at bat: the first base coach and third base coach, who occupy designated coaches' boxes, just outside the foul lines.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] These coaches assist in the direction of baserunners, when the ball is in play, and relay tactical signals from the manager to batters and runners, during pauses in play.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In contrast to many other team sports, baseball managers and coaches generally wear their team's uniforms; coaches must be in uniform to be allowed on the field to confer with players during a game.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Any baseball game involves one or more umpires, who make rulings on the outcome of each play.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] At a minimum, one umpire will stand behind the catcher, to have a good view of the strike zone, and call balls and strikes.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Additional umpires may be stationed near the other bases, thus making it easier to judge plays such as attempted force outs and tag outs.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In MLB, four umpires are used for each game, one near each base.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In the playoffs, six umpires are used: one at each base and two in the outfield along the foul lines.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Many of the pre-game and in-game strategic decisions in baseball revolve around a fundamental fact: in general, right-handed batters tend to be more successful against left-handed pitchers and, to an even greater degree, left-handed batters tend to be more successful against right-handed pitchers.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A manager with several left-handed batters in the regular lineup, who knows the team will be facing a left-handed starting pitcher, may respond by starting one or more of the right-handed backups on the team's roster.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] During the late innings of a game, as relief pitchers and pinch hitters are brought in, the opposing managers will often go back and forth trying to create favorable matchups with their substitutions.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The manager of the fielding team trying to arrange same-handed pitcher-batter matchups and the manager of the batting team trying to arrange opposite-handed matchups.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] With a team that has the lead in the late innings, a manager may remove a starting position player—especially one whose turn at bat is not likely to come up again—for a more skillful fielder (known as a defensive substitution).
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The tactical decision that precedes almost every play in a baseball game involves pitch selection.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] By gripping and then releasing the baseball in a certain manner, and by throwing it at a certain speed, pitchers can cause the baseball to break to either side, or downward, as it approaches the batter, thus creating differing pitches that can be selected.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Among the resulting wide variety of pitches that may be thrown, the four basic types are the fastball, the changeup (or off-speed pitch), and two breaking balls—the curveball and the slider.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Pitchers have different repertoires of pitches they are skillful at throwing.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Conventionally, before each pitch, the catcher signals the pitcher what type of pitch to throw, as well as its general vertical or horizontal location.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] If there is disagreement on the selection, the pitcher may shake off the sign and the catcher will call for a different pitch.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] With a runner on base and taking a lead, the pitcher may attempt a pickoff, a quick throw to a fielder covering the base to keep the runner's lead in check or, optimally, effect a tag out.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Pickoff attempts, however, are subject to rules that severely restrict the pitcher's movements before and during the pickoff attempt.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Violation of any one of these rules could result in the umpire calling a balk against the pitcher, which permits any runners on base to advance one base with impunity.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] If an attempted stolen base is anticipated, the catcher may call for a pitchout, a ball thrown deliberately off the plate, allowing the catcher to catch it while standing and throw quickly to a base.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Facing a batter with a strong tendency to hit to one side of the field, the fielding team may employ a shift, with most or all of the fielders moving to the left or right of their usual positions.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] With a runner on third base, the infielders may play in, moving closer to home plate to improve the odds of throwing out the runner on a ground ball, though a sharply hit grounder is more likely to carry through a drawn-in infield.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Several basic offensive tactics come into play with a runner on first base, including the fundamental choice of whether to attempt a steal of second base.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The hit and run is sometimes employed, with a skillful contact hitter, the runner takes off with the pitch, drawing the shortstop or second baseman over to second base, creating a gap in the infield for the batter to poke the ball through.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The sacrifice bunt, calls for the batter to focus on making soft contact with the ball, so that it rolls a short distance into the infield, allowing the runner to advance into scoring position as the batter is thrown out at first.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A batter, particularly one who is a fast runner, may also attempt to bunt for a hit.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A sacrifice bunt employed with a runner on third base, aimed at bringing that runner home, is known as a squeeze play.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] With a runner on third and fewer than two outs, a batter may instead concentrate on hitting a fly ball that, even if it is caught, will be deep enough to allow the runner to tag up and score—a successful batter, in this case, gets credit for a sacrifice fly.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In order to increase the chance of advancing a batter to first base via a walk, the manager will sometimes signal a batter who is ahead in the count (i.e., has more balls than strikes) to take, or not swing at, the next pitch.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The batter's potential reward of reaching base (via a walk) exceeds the disadvantage if the next pitch is a strike.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Consensus once held that today's baseball is a North American development from the older game rounders, popular among children in Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] American baseball historian David Block suggests that the game originated in England; recently uncovered historical evidence supports this position.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] According to Block and official MLB historian John Thorn, this earlier version of baseball may have involved hitting the ball with a hand, making it akin to today's punchball.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Block argues that rounders and early baseball were actually regional variants of each other, and that the game's most direct antecedents are the English games of stoolball and "tut-ball".
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The earliest known reference to baseball is in a 1744 British publication, *A Little Pretty Pocket-Book*, by John Newbery.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Block discovered that the first recorded game of "Base Ball" took place in 1749 in Surrey, and featured the Prince of Wales as a player.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] This early form of the game was apparently brought to Canada by English immigrants.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] By the early 1830s, there were reports of a variety of uncodified bat-and-ball games recognizable as early forms of baseball being played around North America.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The first recorded baseball game in North America was played in Beachville, Ontario, Canada, on June 4, 1838.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In 1845, Alexander Cartwright, a member of New York City's Knickerbocker Club, led the codification of the so-called Knickerbocker Rules, which in turn were based on rules developed in 1837 by William R.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] While there are reports that the New York Knickerbockers played games in 1845, the contest long recognized as the first recorded baseball game in U.S. history took place on June 19, 1846, in Hoboken, New Jersey: the "New York Nine" defeated the Knickerbockers, 23–1, in four innings.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] With the Knickerbocker code as the basis, the rules of modern baseball continued to evolve over the next half-century.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The game then went on to spread throughout the Pacific Rim and the Americas, with Americans backing the sport as a way to spread American values.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In the mid-1850s, a baseball craze hit the New York metropolitan area, and by 1856, local journals were referring to baseball as the "national pastime" or "national game".
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A year later, the sport's first governing body, the National Association of Base Ball Players, was formed.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In 1867, it barred participation by African Americans.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The more formally structured National League was founded in 1876.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Professional Negro leagues formed, but quickly folded.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In 1887, softball, under the name of indoor baseball or indoor-outdoor, was invented as a winter version of the parent game.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The American League evolved from the minor Western League, which was reorganized under Ban Johnson in 1893.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] It was not until 1901 that the American League was formally established as a major league.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] By 1893, crucial structural changes (like moving the pitching distance to 60 feet, 6 inches) firmly cemented the modern rulebook.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The National Agreement of 1903 formalized relations both between the two major leagues and between them and the National Association of Professional Base Ball Leagues, representing most of the country's minor professional leagues.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The World Series, pitting the two major league champions against each other, was inaugurated that fall.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The Black Sox Scandal of the 1919 World Series led to the formation of the office of the Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The first commissioner, Kenesaw Mountain Landis, was elected in 1920.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] That year also saw the founding of the Negro National League; the first significant Negro league, it would operate until 1931.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] For part of the 1920s, it was joined by the Eastern Colored League.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Compared with the present, professional baseball in the early 20th century was lower-scoring, and pitchers were more dominant.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] This so-called "dead-ball era" ended in the early 1920s with several changes in rule and circumstance that were advantageous to hitters.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Strict new regulations that governed the ball's size, shape and composition, along with a new rule officially banning the spitball and other pitches that depended on the ball being treated or roughed-up with foreign substances, resulted in a ball that traveled farther when hit.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The rise of the legendary player Babe Ruth, the first great power hitter of the new era, helped permanently alter the nature of the game.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Louis Cardinals general manager Branch Rickey invested in several minor league clubs and developed the first modern farm system.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A new Negro National League was organized in 1933; four years later, it was joined by the Negro American League.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The first elections to the National Baseball Hall of Fame took place in 1936.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In 1939, Little League Baseball was founded in Pennsylvania.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Many minor league teams disbanded when World War II led to a player shortage.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Wrigley led the formation of the All-American Girls Professional Baseball League to help keep the game in the public eye.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The first crack in the unwritten agreement barring blacks from white-controlled professional ball occurred in 1945: Jackie Robinson was signed by the National League's Brooklyn Dodgers and began playing for their minor league team in Montreal.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In 1947, Robinson broke the major leagues' color barrier when he debuted with the Dodgers.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Latin-American players, largely overlooked before, also started entering the majors in greater numbers.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In 1951, two Chicago White Sox, Venezuelan-born Chico Carrasquel and black Cuban-born Minnie Miñoso, became the first Hispanic All-Stars.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Integration proceeded slowly: by 1953, only six of the 16 major league teams had a black player on the roster.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In 1975, the union's power—and players' salaries—began to increase greatly when the reserve clause was effectively struck down, leading to the free agency system.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Significant work stoppages occurred in 1981 and 1994, the latter forcing the cancellation of the World Series for the first time in 90 years.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Attendance had been growing steadily since the mid-1970s and in 1994, before the stoppage, the majors were setting their all-time record for per-game attendance.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] After play resumed in 1995, non-division-winning wild card teams became a permanent fixture of the post-season.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Regular-season interleague play was introduced in 1997 and the second-highest attendance mark for a full season was set.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In 2000, the National and American Leagues were dissolved as legal entities.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] While their identities were maintained for scheduling purposes (and the designated hitter distinction), the regulations and other functions—such as player discipline and umpire supervision—they had administered separately were consolidated under the rubric of MLB.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In 2001, Barry Bonds established the current record of 73 home runs in a single season.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In 2007, Bonds became MLB's all-time home run leader, surpassing Hank Aaron, as total major league and minor league attendance both reached all-time highs.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Despite having been called "America's national pastime", baseball is well-established in several other countries.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] As early as 1877, a professional league, the International Association, featured teams from both Canada and the United States.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] While baseball is widely played in Canada and many minor league teams have been based in the country, the American major leagues did not include a Canadian club until 1969, when the Montreal Expos joined the National League as an expansion team.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In 1977, the expansion Toronto Blue Jays joined the American League.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In 1847, American soldiers played what may have been the first baseball game in Mexico at Parque Los Berros in Xalapa, Veracruz.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The first formal baseball league outside of the United States and Canada was founded in 1878 in Cuba, which maintains a rich baseball tradition.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The English football club, Aston Villa, were the first British baseball champions winning the 1890 National League of Baseball of Great Britain.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The 2025 National Champions were the London Mets.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The Dominican Republic held its first islandwide championship tournament in 1912.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Professional baseball tournaments and leagues began to form in other countries between the world wars, including the Netherlands (formed in 1922), Australia (1934), Japan (1936), Mexico (1937), and Puerto Rico (1938).
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The Japanese major leagues have long been considered the highest quality professional circuits outside of the United States.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] After World War II, professional leagues were founded in many Latin American countries, most prominently Venezuela (1946) and the Dominican Republic (1955).
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Since the early 1970s, the annual Caribbean Series has matched the championship clubs from the four leading Latin American winter leagues: the Dominican Professional Baseball League, Mexican Pacific League, Puerto Rican Professional Baseball League, and Venezuelan Professional Baseball League.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In Asia, South Korea (1982), Taiwan (1990) and China (2003) all have professional leagues.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Other European countries have seen professional leagues; the most successful, other than the Dutch league, is the Italian league, founded in 1948.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In 2004, Australia won a surprise silver medal at the Olympic Games.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The Confédération Européene de Baseball (European Baseball Confederation), founded in 1953, organizes a number of competitions between clubs from different countries.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Women's baseball is played on an organized amateur basis in numerous countries.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] After being admitted to the Olympics as a medal sport beginning with the 1992 Games, baseball was dropped from the 2012 Summer Olympic Games at the 2005 International Olympic Committee meeting.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] While the sport's lack of a following in much of the world was a factor, more important was MLB's reluctance to allow its players to participate during the major league season.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] MLB initiated the World Baseball Classic, scheduled to precede its season, partly as a replacement, high-profile international tournament.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The inaugural Classic, held in March 2006, was the first tournament involving national teams to feature a significant number of MLB participants.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The Baseball World Cup was discontinued after its 2011 edition in favor of an expanded World Baseball Classic.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Baseball has certain attributes that set it apart from the other popular team sports in the countries where it has a following.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] All of these sports use a clock, play is less individual, and the variation between playing fields is not as substantial or important.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The comparison between cricket and baseball demonstrates that many of baseball's distinctive elements are shared in various ways with similar sports.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In clock-limited sports, games often end with a team that holds the lead killing the clock rather than competing aggressively against the opposing team.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In contrast, baseball has no clock, thus a team cannot win without getting the last batter out and rallies are not constrained by time.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] At almost any turn in any baseball game, the most advantageous strategy is some form of aggressive strategy.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] While nine innings has been the standard since the beginning of professional baseball, the duration of the average major league game has increased steadily through the years.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] At the turn of the 20th century, games typically took an hour and a half to play.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In the 1920s, they averaged just less than two hours, which eventually ballooned to 2:38 in 1960.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] By 1997, the average American League game lasted 2:57 (National League games were about 10 minutes shorter—pitchers at the plate making for quicker outs than designated hitters).
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In 2004, Major League Baseball declared that its goal was an average game of 2:45.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] By 2014, though, the average MLB game took over three hours to complete.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The lengthening of games is attributed to longer breaks between half-innings for television commercials, increased offense, more pitching changes, and a slower pace of play, with pitchers taking more time between each delivery, and batters stepping out of the box more frequently.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Other leagues have experienced similar issues.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In 2008, Nippon Professional Baseball took steps aimed at shortening games by 12 minutes from the preceding decade's average of 3:18.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In 2016, the average nine-inning playoff game in Major League baseball was 3 hours and 35 minutes.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] This was up 10 minutes from 2015 and 21 minutes from 2014.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In response to the lengthening of the game, MLB decided from the 2023 season onward to institute a pitch clock rule to penalize batters and pitchers who take too much time between pitches; this had the effect of shortening 2023 regular season games by 24 minutes on average.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Although baseball is a team sport, individual players are often placed under scrutiny and pressure.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] While rewarding, it has sometimes been described as "ruthless" due to the pressure on the individual player.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] In 1915, a baseball instructional manual pointed out that every single pitch, of which there are often more than two hundred in a game, involves an individual, one-on-one contest: "the pitcher and the batter in a battle of wits".
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Pitcher, batter, and fielder all act essentially independent of each other.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] While coaching staffs can signal pitcher or batter to pursue certain tactics, the execution of the play itself is a series of solitary acts.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] If the batter hits a line drive, the outfielder is solely responsible for deciding to try to catch it or play it on the bounce and for succeeding or failing.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The statistical precision of baseball is both facilitated by this isolation and reinforces it.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] There is no statistical equivalent in cricket for the fielding error and thus less emphasis on personal responsibility in this area of play.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Unlike those of most sports, baseball playing fields can vary significantly in size and shape.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Major league teams often skirt even this rule.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] For example, at Daikin Park, which became the home of the Houston Astros in 2000, the Crawford Boxes in left field are only 315 feet (96 m) from home plate.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] There are no rules at all that address the height of fences or other structures at the edge of the outfield.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The most famously idiosyncratic outfield boundary is the left-field wall at Boston's Fenway Park, in use since 1912: the Green Monster is 310 feet (94 m) from home plate down the line and 37 feet (11 m) tall.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Similarly, there are no regulations at all concerning the dimensions of foul territory.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Thus a foul fly ball may be entirely out of play in a park with little space between the foul lines and the stands, but a foulout in a park with more expansive foul ground.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A fence in foul territory that is close to the outfield line will tend to direct balls that strike it back toward the fielders, while one that is farther away may actually prompt more collisions, as outfielders run full speed to field balls deep in the corner.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] These variations can make the difference between a double and a triple or inside-the-park home run.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The surface of the field is also unregulated.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] While the adjacent image shows a traditional field surfacing arrangement (and the one used by virtually all MLB teams with naturally surfaced fields), teams are free to decide what areas will be grassed or bare.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Some fields—including several in MLB—use artificial turf.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Surface variations can have a significant effect on how ground balls behave and are fielded as well as on baserunning.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Similarly, the presence of a roof (seven major league teams play in stadiums with permanent or retractable roofs) can greatly affect how fly balls are played.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] While football and soccer players deal with similar variations of field surface and stadium covering, the size and shape of their fields are much more standardized.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The area out-of-bounds on a football or soccer field does not affect play the way foul territory in baseball does, so variations in that regard are largely insignificant.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] These physical variations create a distinctive set of playing conditions at each ballpark.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Other local factors, such as altitude and climate, can also significantly affect play.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A given stadium may acquire a reputation as a pitcher's park or a hitter's park, if one or the other discipline notably benefits from its unique mix of elements.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The most exceptional park in this regard is Coors Field, home of the Colorado Rockies.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Its high altitude—5,282 feet (1,610 m) above sea level—is partly responsible for giving it the strongest hitter's park effect in the major leagues due to the low air pressure.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] Wrigley Field, home of the Chicago Cubs, is known for its fickle disposition: a pitcher's park when the strong winds off Lake Michigan are blowing in, it becomes more of a hitter's park when they are blowing out.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] The absence of a standardized field affects not only how particular games play out, but the nature of team rosters and players' statistical records.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] For example, hitting a fly ball 330 feet (100 m) into right field might result in an easy catch on the warning track at one park, and a home run at another.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] A team that plays in a park with a relatively short right field, such as the New York Yankees, will tend to stock its roster with left-handed pull hitters, who can best exploit it.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p01] On the individual level, a player who spends most of his career with a team that plays in a hitter's park will gain an advantage in batting statistics over time—even more so if his talents are especially suited to the park.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Organized baseball lends itself to statistics to a greater degree than many other sports.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Each play is discrete and has a relatively small number of possible outcomes.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] The Official Baseball Rules administered by MLB require the official scorer to categorize each baseball play unambiguously.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] The rules provide detailed criteria to promote consistency.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] The score report is the official basis for both the box score of the game and the relevant statistical records.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] General managers, managers, and baseball scouts use statistics to evaluate players and make strategic decisions.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Certain traditional statistics are familiar to most baseball fans.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Among the many other statistics that are kept are those collectively known as *situational statistics*.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] For example, statistics can indicate which specific pitchers a certain batter performs best against.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] If a given situation statistically favors a certain batter, the manager of the fielding team may be more likely to change pitchers or have the pitcher intentionally walk the batter in order to face one who is less likely to succeed.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Sabermetrics is the field of baseball statistical study and the development of new statistics and analytical tools.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Such new statistics are also called sabermetrics.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] The term was coined around 1980 by one of the field's leading proponents, Bill James, and derives from the Society for American Baseball Research (SABR).
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Writing in 1919, philosopher Morris Raphael Cohen described baseball as the national religion of the US.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] In the words of sports columnist Jayson Stark, baseball has long been "a unique paragon of American culture"—a status he sees as devastated by the steroid abuse scandal.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] American influence in the Western Hemisphere has meant that baseball grew significantly in the region.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] A century later, the situation was very different.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] With the rise in popularity of other team sports with much higher average ticket prices—football, basketball, and hockey—professional baseball had become among the most popular blue-collar-oriented American spectator sports.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Overall, baseball has a large following in the United States; a 2006 poll found that nearly half of Americans are fans.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] This led to baseball being granted the title of "America's favorite pastime" by many American baseball fans.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] As historians and scholars now speculate, baseball is a metaphor of the American way of life In the late 1900s and early 2000s, baseball's position compared to football in the United States moved in contradictory directions.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] In 2008, MLB set a revenue record of $6.5 billion, matching the NFL's revenue for the first time in decades.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] A new MLB revenue record of more than $10 billion was set in 2017.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] On the other hand, the percentage of American sports fans polled who named baseball as their favorite sport was 9%, compared to pro football at 37%.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] In 1985, the respective figures were pro football 24%, baseball 23%.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Because there are so many more major league games played, there is no comparison in overall attendance.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] In 2008, total attendance at major league games was the second-highest in history: 78.6 million, 0.7% off the record set the previous year.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] The following year, amid the U.S. recession, attendance fell by 6.6% to 73.4 million.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Eight years later, it dropped under 73 million.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Attendance at games held under the Minor League Baseball umbrella set a record in 2008, with 43.3 million.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] While MLB games have not drawn the same national TV viewership as football games, MLB games are dominant in teams' local markets and regularly lead all programs in primetime in their markets during the summer.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] After multiple years of declines since 2017, baseball attendance has grown slightly in recent years.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] In 2024, attendance was 71.3 million, the highest since 2017.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Baseball is very popular in Venezuela; in 2011, 95% of people surveyed claimed it to be the national sport.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] In Nicaragua and Panama, baseball is also considered the national sport.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] While soccer is still more popular, baseball is a fast-growing sport in Mexico.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] In 2024, top Mexican League baseball teams outdraw some Liga MX teams in attendance.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Baseball also is somewhat popular in Colombia, though secondary to soccer, especially in coastal areas such as Barranquilla and Cartagena which are near the Caribbean.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] In recent years, baseball has grown in popularity in Colombia, especially in the capital of Bogotá, due an increase of Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] In Brazil, baseball fan popularity has grown in the last few years, thanks to MLB broadcasts in Brazilian ESPN and the historic silver medal in 2023 Pan-American games.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] However, it still lags behind basketball and American football in the list of most played sports in Brazil.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Baseball has also grown in popularity in Argentina and Peru in recent years due to Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Costa Rica has also seen a growth in the popularity of baseball.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Since 1987, baseballs have exclusively been made in the Costa Rican town of Turrialba.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] In recent years, Major leaguer Mauricio Dubón has made efforts to increase support for the sport in the country.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] The sport's overall popularity in Latin America has assisted in integrating Latin American migrants to the United States.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Since the early 1980s, the Dominican Republic, in particular the city of San Pedro de Macorís, has been the major leagues' primary source of foreign talent.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] In 2017, 83 of the 868 players on MLB Opening Day rosters (and disabled lists) were from the country.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Among other Caribbean countries and territories, a combined 97 MLB players were born in Venezuela, Cuba, and Puerto Rico.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Hall-of-Famer Roberto Clemente remains one of the greatest national heroes in Puerto Rico's history.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] While baseball has long been the island's primary athletic pastime, its once well-attended professional winter league has declined in popularity since 1990, when young Puerto Rican players began to be included in the major leagues' annual first-year player draft.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] In Cuba, where baseball is by every reckoning the national sport, the national team overshadows the city and provincial teams that play in the top-level domestic leagues.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Baseball is also one of the most popular sports of Aruba and Curaçao, and a growing sport in The Bahamas and the US Virgin Islands.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] In East Asia, baseball is among the most popular sports in Japan, Taiwan and South Korea.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] In Japan, where baseball is inarguably the leading spectator team sport, combined revenue for the twelve teams in Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the body that oversees both the Central and Pacific Leagues, was estimated at $1 billion in 2007.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Total NPB attendance for the year was approximately 20 million.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] While in the preceding two decades, MLB attendance grew by 50 percent and revenue nearly tripled, the comparable NPB figures were stagnant.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] There are concerns that MLB's growing interest in acquiring star Japanese players will hurt the game in their home country.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Revenue figures are not released for the country's amateur system.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Similarly, according to one official pronouncement, the sport's governing authority "has never taken into account attendance ... because its greatest interest has always been the development of athletes".
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] In Taiwan, baseball is one of the most widely spectated sports, in TV and person.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown significantly in China in recent years, with MLB estimating in 2019 that there are 21 million active fans in the country.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Baseball was considered a national pastime in the Philippines in the 1960s and 70s, but the sport has since declined in popularity.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Since 2005, there have been efforts to revitalize the sport in the country.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Baseball saw a surge in popularity in Thailand following the countries' silver medal in baseball in the 2025 SEA Games, which were hosted in Thailand.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Baseball is generally a niche sport in Europe.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] However, baseball is somewhat popular in the Netherlands, where it is known as *honkbal*, thanks to influence from the United States after World War II and the Kingdoms control over Aruba and Curaçao where it is the most popular sport.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Baseball is also somewhat popular in portions of Italy, especially in the town of Nettuno, due to influence from American soldiers after World War II.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown in recent years in the Czech Republic, due in part to the Czech teams' success in the 2023 World Baseball Classic.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Baseball is one of the most popular sports in Palau and Guam.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] In Australia, baseball is a niche sport but the country does have a professional league.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Because the league is played in winter for the western hemisphere, it attracts American and Korean professional players looking to play winter league baseball.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] In 2026, there were more than 30 Australians playing college baseball in the United States compared to six in 2020.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] The Dodgers operate a large baseball academy in Mpigi, Uganda, and there are also baseball programs in Luwero, Uganda.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] There is also a Africa Baseball Academy in Nairobi, Nigeria.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Baseball was popular in South Africa prior to World War 2 but popularity has since waned.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] There are still teams and attempts to raise the popularity of baseball in the country, including the introduction of Baseball5.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] There is a growing baseball program in South Sudan, which has resulted in professional contracts.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] The Japan-Africa Baseball & Softball Foundation has created Koshien high school baseball tournaments in Tanzania, Ghana and Kenya, which Tanzania being the most successful.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] There are further plans for similar tournaments in Nigeria, South Sudan, Benin, Cameroon and Zambia.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] As of 2024, Little League Baseball oversees leagues with 2 million participants in more than 80 countries.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] The number of players has fallen since the 1990s, when 3 million children took part in Little League Baseball annually.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Babe Ruth League teams have over 1 million participants.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] According to the president of the International Baseball Federation in 2009, between 300,000 and 500,000 women and girls play baseball around the world, including Little League and the introductory game of Tee Ball.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] A varsity baseball team is an established part of physical education departments at most high schools and colleges in the United States.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] In 2015, nearly half a million high schoolers and over 34,000 collegians played on their schools' baseball teams.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] By early in the 20th century, intercollegiate baseball was Japan's leading sport.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Today, high school baseball in particular is immensely popular there.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] The final rounds of the two annual tournaments—the National High School Baseball Invitational Tournament in the spring, and the even more important National High School Baseball Championship in the summer—are broadcast around the country.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] The tournaments are known, respectively, as Spring Koshien and Summer Koshien after the 55,000-capacity stadium where they are played.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] In Cuba, baseball is a mandatory part of the state system of physical education, which begins at age six.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Talented children as young as seven are sent to special district schools for more intensive training—the first step on a ladder whose acme is the national baseball team.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Baseball has had a broad impact on popular culture, both in the United States and elsewhere.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Dozens of English-language idioms have been derived from baseball; in particular, the game is the source of a number of widely used sexual euphemisms.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] The first networked radio broadcasts in North America were of the 1922 World Series: famed sportswriter Grantland Rice announced play-by-play from New York City's Polo Grounds on WJZ–Newark, New Jersey, which was connected by wire to WGY–Schenectady, New York, and WBZ–Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] The baseball cap has become a ubiquitous fashion item not only in the United States and Japan, but also in countries where the sport itself is not particularly popular, such as the United Kingdom.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Baseball has inspired many works of art and entertainment.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] There have been many baseball movies, including the Academy Award–winning *The Pride of the Yankees* (1942) and the Oscar nominees *The Natural* (1984) and *Field of Dreams* (1989).
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] The American Film Institute's selection of the ten best sports movies includes *The Pride of the Yankees* at number 3 and *Bull Durham* (1988) at number 5.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Baseball has provided thematic material for hits on both stage—the Adler–Ross musical *Damn Yankees*—and record—George J.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Gaskin's "Slide, Kelly, Slide", Simon and Garfunkel's "Mrs.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Robinson", and John Fogerty's "Centerfield".
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] The baseball-inspired comedic sketch "Who's on First?", popularized by Abbott and Costello in 1938, quickly became famous; six decades later, *Time* named it the best comedy routine of the 20th century.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Literary works connected to the game include the short fiction of Ring Lardner and novels such as Bernard Malamud's *The Natural* (the source for the movie), Robert Coover's *The Universal Baseball Association, Inc., J.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Henry Waugh, Prop.*, John Grisham's Calico Joe and W.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Kinsella's *Shoeless Joe* (the source for *Field of Dreams*).
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Baseball's literary canon also includes the beat reportage of Damon Runyon; the columns of Grantland Rice, Red Smith, Dick Young, and Peter Gammons; and the essays of Roger Angell.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Among the celebrated nonfiction books in the field are Lawrence S.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Ritter's *The Glory of Their Times*, Roger Kahn's *The Boys of Summer*, and Michael Lewis's *Moneyball*.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] The 1970 publication of major league pitcher Jim Bouton's tell-all chronicle *Ball Four* is considered a turning point in the reporting of professional sports.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Baseball has also inspired the creation of new cultural forms.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Baseball cards were introduced in the late 19th century as trade cards.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] A typical example featured an image of a baseball player on one side and advertising for a business on the other.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] In the early 1900s they were produced widely as promotional items by tobacco and confectionery companies.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] The 1930s saw the popularization of the modern style of baseball card, with a player photograph accompanied on the rear by statistics and biographical data.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Baseball cards—many of which are now prized collectibles—are the source of the much broader trading card industry, involving similar products for different sports and non-sports-related fields.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Modern fantasy sports began in 1980 with the invention of Rotisserie League Baseball by New York writer Daniel Okrent and several friends.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Participants in a Rotisserie league draft notional teams from the list of active MLB players and play out an entire imaginary season with game outcomes based on the players' latest real-world statistics.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Rotisserie-style play quickly became a phenomenon.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Now known more generically as fantasy baseball, it has inspired similar games based on an array of different sports.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] The field boomed with increasing Internet access and new fantasy sports-related websites.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] By 2008, 29.9 million people in the United States and Canada were playing fantasy sports, spending $800 million on the hobby.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] The burgeoning popularity of fantasy baseball is also credited with the increasing attention paid to sabermetrics—first among fans, only later among baseball professionals.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Informal variations of baseball have popped up over time, with games like corkball reflecting local traditions and allowing the game to be played in diverse environments.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Two variations of baseball, softball and Baseball5, are internationally governed alongside baseball by the World Baseball Softball Confederation.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] American professional baseball teams toured Britain in 1874 and 1889, and had a great effect on similar sports in Britain.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] In Wales and Merseyside, a strong community game had already developed with skills and plays more in keeping with the American game and the Welsh began to informally adopt the name "baseball" (Pêl Fas), to reflect the American style.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] By the 1890s, calls were made to follow the success of other working class sports (like Rugby in Wales and Soccer in Merseyside) and adopt a distinct set of rules and bureaucracy.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] During the 1892 season rules for the game of "baseball" were agreed and the game was officially codified.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] Finnish baseball, also known as pesäpallo, is a combination of traditional ball-batting team games and North American baseball, invented by Lauri "Tahko" Pihkala in the 1920s.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] The basic idea of pesäpallo is similar to that of baseball: the offense tries to score by hitting the ball successfully and running through the bases, while the defense tries to put the batter and runners out.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] One of the most important differences between pesäpallo and baseball is that the ball is pitched vertically, which makes hitting the ball, as well as controlling the power and direction of the hit, much easier.
[src:bete-ombro/baseball-p02] This gives the offensive game more variety, speed, and tactical aspects compared to baseball.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] The teams alternate between "batting" (offensive role), sometimes called "in at bat" or simply *in*, and "fielding" (defensive role), also called "out in the field" or *out*.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] Only the batting team may score, but teams have equal opportunities in both roles.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] The action starts when a player on the fielding team (the "bowler" or "pitcher") puts the ball in play with a delivery whose restriction depends on the game.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] A player on the batting team attempts to strike the delivered ball, commonly with a "bat", which is a club whose dimensions and other aspects are governed by the rules of the game.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] If the ball is not fairly delivered to the batter (i.e. not thrown within his reach), then penalties generally are awarded that help the batting team score.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] The batter generally has an obligation to hit certain balls that are delivered within his reach (i.e. balls aimed at a designated area, known as the strike zone or wicket), and must hit the ball so that it is not caught by a fielder before it touches the ground.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] The most desirable outcome for the batter is generally to hit the ball out of the field, as this results in automatically scoring runs; however, in certain bat-and-ball games, this can result in a penalty against the batter.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] If the ball is struck into the field, then the batter may become a runner trying to reach a safe haven or "base"/"ground".
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] While in contact with a base, the runner is "safe" from the fielding team and in a position to score runs.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] Leaving a safe haven places the runner in danger of being put out (eliminated).
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] The teams switch roles when the fielding team 'puts out'/'gets out' enough of the batting team's players, which varies by game.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] In modern baseball, the fielders put three *players* out.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] In cricket, they "dismiss" all players but one, though in some forms of cricket, there is a limit on the number of deliveries (scoring opportunities) that each team can have, such that the fielding team can become the batting team without getting anyone out.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] Some games permit multiple runners and some have multiple bases to run in sequence.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] Batting may occur, and running begin (and potentially end), at one of the bases.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] The movement between those "safe havens" is governed by the rules of the particular sport.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] The game ends when the losing team has completed the maximum number of innings (batting/scoring turns), which may range from 1 (as in limited-overs cricket) to 9 (as in baseball) or more.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] Ties are generally broken (if at all) by allowing each team to have an additional turn to score.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] Some variations of bat-and-ball games do not feature bats, with batters instead using parts of their bodies to hit the ball; these variations may also give the batter possession of the ball at the start of each play, eliminating the defensive team's role in starting the action.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] A prominent example of this is Baseball5, one of the main sporting disciplines governed by the World Baseball Softball Confederation along with baseball and softball.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] The history of baseball's formation and rise in popularity took place in England (potentially influenced by or descended from games played in continental Europe) and then America.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] Predecessors of baseball were brought to America during the colonial era by English immigrants who played games similar to rounders; at the time, cricket was significantly more popular in the United States, since it was one of the main sports throughout the British Empire.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] However, the main format of cricket was first-class cricket, in which games lasted multiple days; baseball by comparison was a game that lasted less than two hours.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] Because of the vast difference in the duration of the two sports and for other reasons, such as the rising American desire to have some type of national game distinct from England's games, baseball began to grow in America, especially among some of the non-English demographics.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] Some attempts were made to nativize cricket in a way that would reduce its length and other perceived disadvantages relative to baseball; one example of this was wicket, an American variation of cricket which could be played in an afternoon.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] But by the time of the 1860s Civil War, baseball had begun to overtake cricket in popularity; one reason for this was that troops during the Civil War preferred to play baseball, as it did not require a specialized playing surface like the cricket pitch.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] After the Civil War, baseball became a much more organized sport than cricket in America, with more money and competition available to baseball players across the country; thus, several professional cricket players switched to playing baseball, and cricket faded away in America.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] Baseball then began to spread throughout the Pacific Rim and the Americas, supported by the contemporary westward expansion of the United States.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] Over time, several variations of baseball appeared, with some being informal (kickball), others becoming professional sports in their own right (softball), and some even taking root overseas (pesäpallo).
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] In other countries that were part of the British Empire, cricket slowly emerged as the game of choice for the colonizers to spread their culture and values among the colonized.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] Some of the colonized people adapted to playing cricket in order to win the favor of the British, while in other cases, colonized peoples played cricket as a way of beating the British at their own sports, and thus proving themselves as equals.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] This helped to cement cricket as part of the national culture of several countries that later won their independence from the British.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] (right) have sped up baseball and cricket respectively, with the aim of attracting new fans.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] In 1971, the ODI (One Day International) format of cricket was first played internationally; the ODI format shortened cricket from a five-day long game (Test cricket) to a one-day long game.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] In 2003, a new format of cricket called T20 cricket emerged which was designed to last only about three hours.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] By this time, the average MLB game had gone from being two hours long to about three hours long, so the two sports now had formats that were of a comparable duration.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] Later on, the T10 format of cricket, in which games last less than two hours, emerged at a domestic level, with leagues being started for it in several major cricket-playing countries.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] There is a great deal of variation among bat-and-ball games; for example, more runs are generally scored in a cricket match than dozens of baseball games combined, and while a T10 cricket match generally ends in 90 minutes, a Test cricket batter may bat for hours over several consecutive days.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] In cricket and baseball, the playing field is large (at the highest levels of each sport, the minimum distance between the two furthest ends of the field is about 400 to 500 feet (120 to 150 m)), and is divided into an infield and outfield (based on proximity to the batting area).
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] Cricket has the delivery and hitting of the ball done in the same area where the batters can run (the cricket pitch), while baseball does the running in a separate area.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] Most bat-and-ball games have playing area in front of the batter (such as Schlagball), but may (like baseball) restrict batters from hitting the ball behind themselves or too far to the side; see foul territory.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] Bat-and-ball sports can be modified to be played in an indoor court.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] For example, indoor cricket takes place in a 30 by 12 metres (98 ft × 39 ft) facility, while Baseball5 is played on a 21 metres (69 ft)-square field.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] In baseball-like games, the fielders (also known as "position players") operate in a standard set of baseball positions because it is generally possible to cover most of the field by spacing the fielders out in certain ways.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] By contrast, the significantly larger cricket field has many possible cricket fielding positions, with the 11 fielders occupying the slips cordon behind the batter, or other areas of the field.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] T20 cricket and baseball both last about 3 hours, while other forms of cricket can last either multiple days or less than three hours.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] In some bat-and-ball sports, there are team penalties designed to ensure the game goes at a faster pace.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] For example, in various formats of cricket, there are over rate penalties which kick in if a team has bowled too few deliveries within an allotted amount of time, while in some baseball leagues, there is a pitch clock that penalizes batters and pitchers for taking too much time between pitches.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] When one of the teams is not leading and only they have completed all of their allotted batting turns, this allows the other team to win automatically by surpassing the number of runs scored by the first team.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] In cricket, this situation is referred to as a "run chase", with the "target" of the batting team being the number of runs scored by the other team plus one.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] The result may also mention how many more times the losing team batted than the winning team.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] In some circumstances (e.g. bad weather), a complete game may not be possible in its originally envisioned timeframe because of weather or other reasons.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] In baseball-like games, which generally have many innings, it is possible to call the result of a game after both teams have batted only a few of their scheduled turns, or otherwise to finish/replay the game at a later date.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] In cricket, however, which is generally played to only one or two batting turns per team, a match may not be callable for the simple reason that only one of the teams has had the chance to score so far.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] Bat-and-ball games can be played with modified rules in unorthodox places, such as in the street or the backyard.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] Oftentimes, players are forbidden or penalized for hitting the ball out of the field into an area where it would be hard to reach, and play may be modified so as to ensure all players have an opportunity to participate, such as in Kwik cricket.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] At the international level, the World Baseball Classic is the premier baseball tournament.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] For cricket, the ODI World Cup, ICC T20 World Cup, and ICC World Test Championship are the premier tournaments.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] The Pesäpallo World Cup is played every 3 years.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] At the domestic level, baseball tends to be played in leagues with 2 major divisions, with the playoffs being contested in a best-of-seven format.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] T20 leagues in cricket tend to have 6 to 8 teams and follow the Page playoff system (two semi-finals, with an additional match played to determine which team enters the second semi-final, followed by a final).
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] Gilli Danda (which is related to several other traditional games in other parts of the world) is a South Asian game with similarities to baseball and cricket.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] The aim of the game is for the batter to knock a stick on the ground up into the air using a stick held in the hand, and then to hit the airborne stick as far as possible.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] The batter is out if the stick is caught by a player on the other team before it touches the ground.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] Points are earned either based on the distance the stick travels, or by the batter running to a designated area while the fielders collect the batted stick and throw it back to the hitting area to try to get the batter out.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] The game ends after each team has batted once, with each team batting until all of its players are out.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] Striking the ball with a "bat" or any type of stick, or having the defensive team deliver the ball to the batter, is not crucial.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] These games use the foot or hand to hit the ball, and make it significantly easier to hit the ball overall, either by placing significant restrictions on the way the defensive team delivers the ball to the batter, or by giving the batter possession of the ball at the start of each play.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] Otherwise their rules may be similar or even identical to baseball or cricket.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-and-ball-game-p01] The first two use a large (35 cm) soft ball.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] In baseball, a **bat flip** is the throwing of a baseball bat after a hit so that it travels an unusual distance or rotates more than once before landing.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] It is typically done by a batter to show off after hitting a home run, and contrasts with the usual practice of simply dropping the bat as the batter begins running to first base.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] Bat flipping is popular in Asian and Latin American baseball leagues.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] In South Korea, the bat flipping tradition dates to the 1990s, and has become increasingly frequent in the Korea Baseball Organization.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] It is not considered disrespectful and there is no retaliation in the Korean League.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] In the Korean language, bat flips are referred as *ppa-dun* (Korean: 빠던), a portmanteau of the first syllables of the words for "bat" and "throw".
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] The practice is also common in Japan and Taiwan.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] In Canada and the United States, bat flips have traditionally been considered rude and inconsistent with baseball etiquette.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] Traditional etiquette and the unwritten rules of baseball espouse humility and discourage actions that may be interpreted as arrogant or showing up the opponents.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] Torii Hunter, a retired Major League Baseball player and fan of bat flips in Korean baseball, has said that a player throwing a bat in such a manner during a game in the United States would likely face retaliation in a subsequent at bat, such as being hit by a pitch.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] However, bat flips can also be seen as creative and exciting There has also been criticism of criticism about bat flips given how they are often celebrated by leagues for promotional purposes.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] The benches would clear twice in that inning after the home run.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] Bautista was criticized for the bat flip, which he attributed to a failure to understand differences in cultural backgrounds of players, which he said was unplanned and was "caught up in the emotion of the moment".
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] It just happened", and that he was "caught up in the emotion of the moment" when he flipped the bat.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] The Bautista bat flip became an internet meme.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] Fans posted numerous responses to the event on Twitter, and shared videos on Vine and other social media websites and mobile apps.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] It was etched onto jack-o'-lanterns for Halloween, printed on T-shirts and Christmas sweaters, and was also the subject of a thigh tattoo for an Oshawa, Ontario man.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] It was commemorated on a Topps 2016 Series 1 baseball card.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] A corn maze in the Canadian province of New Brunswick was designed with the likeness of the Bautista bat flip.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] The bat flip fueled the rivalry between Toronto and Texas.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] Presumably in retaliation for the bat flip, Texas pitcher Matt Bush hit Bautista with a pitch in the eighth inning of a game on May 15, 2016.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] Shortly after being hit by the pitch, Bautista made a late, hard slide (the variety of which had been made illegal after a separate incident during a National League Division Series game in the same postseason as the bat flip) into Texas second baseman Rougned Odor.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] Odor took exception to the slide and shoved Bautista.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] Bautista stepped toward Odor and appeared to cock his arm, whereupon Odor punched Bautista in the face knocking his glasses and helmet off.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] Odor received an eight-game suspension (later reduced to seven) and Bautista was suspended one game.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] Like the bat flip, images of the punch stoked an internet meme.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] Fans posted numerous images and references on Twitter, Vine, Reddit, and other social media websites.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] Odor has declined to sign images of the punch.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] The two teams faced each other in the ALDS again in 2016, and the Blue Jays won in a 3-game sweep; in Game 1 Bautista hit a three-run home run and then emphatically slammed down the bat in celebration.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] In cricket, the term bat flip refers to the tossing of a bat, instead of a coin, to decide which of the 2 teams in a match will be given the option to decide whether it wants to bat or bowl first.
[src:bete-ombro/bat-flip] Additionally, instead of calling "heads" or "tails", the player calling the toss will call "hills" or "flats" depending on which side of the bat they think will land facing up (i.e., the flat side of the bat or the raised side of the bat).
[src:bete-ombro/bete-ombro] Prince Harry played it on a trip to Brazil.
[src:bete-ombro/bete-ombro] Taco has been credited with helping to grow and influence women's cricket in Brazil.
[src:bete-ombro/bete-ombro] There has been a "World Cup of Bets" held in Brazil, with teams from four cities, in 2016.
[src:bete-ombro/bete-ombro] When introducing cricket to Brazilian audiences, Brazilian media sometimes compare it to bete-ombro.
[src:bete-ombro/bete-ombro] Bete-ombro may have been more popular in the 1990s than it is now.
[src:bete-ombro/bete-ombro] Each of the two fielding players stands behind one of the wickets (called "alvos" (targets) or "casinha" (small house) in Portuguese), and each of the batters in front of one of the wickets.
[src:bete-ombro/bete-ombro] Whichever fielder has the ball throws it to the batter at the opposing wicket, with the other fielder being a de facto wicketkeeper.
[src:bete-ombro/bete-ombro] The batter may try to hit the ball; if he misses, he must place his bat in his crease to avoid being stumped (unlike cricket, the batter's body can't be used for this purpose), which is generally a circle drawn on the ground in front of the wicket.
[src:bete-ombro/bete-ombro] Similar to the bat flip in cricket, there is the "wet or dry" method of deciding which team bats first in bete-ombro: first, one side of the bat is wetted, and then the bat is thrown up in the air.
[src:bete-ombro/bete-ombro] The team that correctly calls whether the wet or dry side of the bat will fall face-up chooses whether to bat or bowl first.
[src:bete-ombro/bete-ombro] (Unlike a cricket bat, both sides of the bete-ombro bat are flat, so it wouldn't be possible to call "Hills or Flats").
[src:bete-ombro/bete-ombro] There is a rule reminiscent of strikeouts in baseball: if the ball goes behind the batter 3 times, then they are out.
[src:bete-ombro/bete-ombro] The game ends when one team gets 12 or 25 points, though there may be additional conditions.
[src:bete-ombro/bete-ombro] In some parts of Brazil, the expression "largar os betes" (to drop the bats) is used to mean "to give up".
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Blind cricket was invented in Melbourne in 1922 by two blind factory workers who improvised the game using a tin can containing rocks.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The Victorian Blind Cricket Association was founded shortly after, in 1922, and the first sports ground and clubhouse for blind cricket was built at Kooyong, Melbourne in 1928.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The world's first test cricket match for the blind was played in 2000 between Pakistan and South Africa, in which Pakistan defeated South Africa by 94 runs.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] South Africa won the first world championship in 1998, defeating Pakistan in the finals; Pakistan consecutively won the next two championships, defeating South Africa and India in the finals in 2002 and 2006.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] In 2014, the championship was won by India, defeating the two-time winner Pakistan.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The rules of blind cricket are based on the standard laws of cricket with some essential modifications.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] WBCC international playing rules are codified in 25 clauses, first ratified in 2005.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] There are a total number of 11 players in each team: at least four players who are totally blind (classified as B1) and three partially blind players (B2), and up to four partially sighted players (B3).
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] In terms of playing equipment, the major adaptation is the ball, which is significantly larger than a standard cricket ball and filled with ball bearings to provide audible cues.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The size allows partially sighted players to see the ball and the contents allow blind players to hear it.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The wicket (stumps) is also larger, made of metal tubes painted in fluorescent colours, to allow partially sighted players to see and blind players to touch it in order to correctly orient themselves when batting or bowling.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Various other modifications to the rules apply.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Verbal signals are widely used both by umpires and players: in particular, the bowler must shout 'Play!' as he releases the ball.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The delivery is required to pitch at least twice when bowled to a completely blind batsman (once when bowled to a partially sighted batsman), but must not be rolling.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Totally blind batsmen cannot be out due to being stumped, and must be found to be LBW twice before going out.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Totally blind fielders are allowed to take a catch on the bounce.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The WBCC was established in 1996 during an international cricket meeting held in New Delhi, India in September 1996.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The WBCC was set up with the objective of promoting and administering the game of blind cricket globally.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Today the WBCC has 10 full members namely Australia, Bangladesh, England, India, New Zealand, South Africa, Sri Lanka, Pakistan, West Indies and Nepal.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] George Abraham of India is the founding Chairman of the WBCC.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Under his leadership, the inaugural Blind Cricket World Cup was held in New Delhi in November 1998.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Peter Donovan of Australia took over as chairman in 2004.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] In November 2008, George Abraham was re-elected as president of the WBCC.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The first World Cup Cricket for the blind competition was held in New Delhi, India.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The tournament was named & designated as, "Kanishka World Cup Cricket for the Blind", because of the sponsorship by Hotel Kanishka of Ministry of Tourism Government of India, as informed by the then Director Administration, Retd.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Col Sardev Singh from the Indian Army and his daughter Rakhee who was volunteering for this tournament.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Further to this, a major portion of the expenses for stay & important events held for all the teams; management /players were borne by Hotel Kanishka.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] A suite was also provided for meetings & management to work from within the hotel.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The match resulted in South Africa winning against Pakistan in the final.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] India and Australia were the two semi-finalists.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The second World Cup was held in Chennai, India in December.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Pakistan defeated South Africa in the finals.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The third World Cup was held in Islamabad, Pakistan defeated India, under the leadership of Aga Shaukat-Ali, the founder of Pakistan Blind Cricket Council.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] On 7 December 2014, India defeated Pakistan in the final at Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] On 20 January 2018, India defeated Pakistan in the final at Sharjah.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The first T20 Blind Cricket World Cup was held at Aditya Academy Ground in Bangalore, India in 2012.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] India defeated Pakistan by 29 runs in the final.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The **2017 Blind World T20** also known as **2017 Blind T20 World Cup** was a T20I tournament which was also the second edition of the Blind T20 World Cup for blind cricketers, held in India from 30 January to 12 February.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] India defeated Pakistan by 9 wickets in the finals to win their second Blind T20 World Cup.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Ten teams, hosts India, Pakistan, Sri Lanka, England, Bangladesh, West Indies, South Africa, Nepal, Australia and New Zealand took part, playing in 48 matches.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] On 12 February 2017, India defeated Pakistan in the final at Bengaluru, India.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] On 17 December 2022, India defeated Bangladesh at Bengaluru, India.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] On December 3, 2024, Pakistan has won the Blind T20 World Cup 2024 by beating Bangladesh by 10 wickets in the final match played in Multan, Pakistan.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Pakistan achieved the target without losing a single wicket, securing a decisive victory.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The first Women's T20 Blind Cricket World Cup was held at Colombo, Sri Lanka from November 11 to November 23, 2025.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] India won the cup by beating Nepal by seven wickets.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The tournament featured six teams - India, Nepal, Pakistan, Sri Lanka, Australia and the US - in a single round-robin.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The founding members of the British Blind Sport organisation were cricketers, and the association is the administrative body for the sport within the United Kingdom.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Blind Cricket New South Wales (BCNSW) is the home of blind cricket in New South Wales.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Starting 2011, Cricket Association for the Blind in India (CABI) is in place of Association for Cricket for the Blind India (ACBI) set up in 1996.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] George Abraham is the founder of the registered voluntary body.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Its objectives are to use competitive cricket to teach the blind to look at life positively, gain in confidence and strive to be winners rather than dependents; and to use the game as a medium to transmit the message of ability and talent to the society.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The ACBI organised the first two Blind Cricket World Cups in 1998 and 2002.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] CABI is the apex body that organizes and conducts cricket for blind across India.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] CABI is a sports initiative of Samarthanam Trust for the Disabled.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] It is a registered Non Profit Organization, affiliated to the World Blind Cricket Council (WBCC).
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Conferred the hosting rights of the First Ever T – 20 World Cup in Bangalore in November /December 2012.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] In 1997, Agha Shoukat Ali laid the foundation for the development of cricket for the blind in Pakistan named 'Pakistan Blind Cricket Council' (PBCC).
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Agha Shoukat Ali, the founder and life and soul of cricket for the blind in Pakistan, also represented the country in August 1996 the first International Conference on Cricket for the Blind which was held in Delhi, India, in which seven countries from all over the World participated.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The Pakistan Blind Cricket Council is registered and affiliated with the World Blind Cricket Council (WBCC) and is its permanent member.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The PBCC attends all the International Conferences and is playing its part practically.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] From 1997 onwards many registered clubs have come into existence and are affiliated with the Pakistan Blind Cricket Council.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Cricket is now played regularly in schools among the blind.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Tournaments are regularly organized in different cities of the country so that the blind may be able to meet, exchange information and have some fun.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Rules similar to 'sighted cricket' are observed for cricket for the blind whenever it is played and efforts are being made to spread this all over the country.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] In 2002 Government of Punjab allocated 45 Kanal space for the construction of Cricket stadium and facilities for PBCC.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] On construction it will be the first Cricket stadium built for Blind Cricketers.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The Victorian Blind Cricket Association (VBCA) is the home of blind cricket in Victoria.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Blind cricket was invented in Melbourne in 1922.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The world's first sports ground and clubhouse for blind people was developed at Kooyong, Victoria in 1928 and is still used today as the home of the VBCA.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The Association now has four clubs with approximately 70 vision-impaired and blind members and several volunteers.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The Victorian Blind Cricket Association is located in the Charlie Bradley Pavilion, at the rear of 454 Glenferrie Road, Kooyong VIC 3144 (opposite the Kooyong Tennis Stadium Kooyong Stadium).
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Games are played on Saturday afternoons from October through to March and spectators are most welcome.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The VBCA provides an important role in the community by developing and providing opportunities for people who are blind or vision impaired to enjoy the recreational and social benefits of cricket.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Additionally, the VBCA participates in cricket matches against sighted opposition in keeping with the philosophy of integration and working to remove barriers and isolating influences of having limited vision.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Blind cricket is widely played in Australia, with teams playing regular fixtures in the states of Queensland, New South Wales, Victoria, South Australia and Western Australia, as well as in the Australian Capital Territory.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Every two years State cricket teams meet for the Australian Blind Cricket Championships.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The 31st National Blind Cricket Championships was held in Queensland in 2012.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The first blind cricket "Ashes" competition was held in England in August 2004.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Five one-day matches were played, with England winning the Ashes by three games to two.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] A return series of five matches was held in Sydney, Australia, in December 2008, resulting in a controversial 3–0 victory for England.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Australia was victorious in a 2012 contest but England regained the ascendancy in 2016.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Samarthanam Trust for the Disabled & Cricket Association for the Blind in India (CABI organizes state, zonal, national and international level cricket tournaments for the blind.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The state level cricket tournaments are organized to select the best state team to participate in their respective zones (north, east, west and south).
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Zonal matches are held by Samarthanam and CABI by identifying local partners, including private and government bodies which affiliate with the organizers, lending their support to the tournament.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The winners of the zonal matches play league matches to qualify for the finals.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The first regular match for the blind was played in Karachi in 1978 between Lahore and IDA RIEU School, Karachi.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] During this period several matches were played at school level.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The PBCC has organized eight (8) major National Tournaments besides Two Double-Wicket Tournaments since it is established in 1997.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Blind Cricket South Africa (BCSA) is the governing body for blind cricket in South Africa.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] It was founded in 2008 with the aim of promoting and developing the sport of cricket for the blind and visually impaired in the country.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The organization oversees regional activities throughout the country, including in Gauteng, KwaZulu-Natal, the Western Cape, and the Free State.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] These regional activities include leagues, tournaments, and training programs for blind and visually impaired cricketers.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] Blind cricket in South Africa has grown significantly since the formation of BCSA, with increasing numbers of players and teams participating in regional and national competitions.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The organization has also established partnerships with other cricketing bodies, including Cricket South Africa, to further promote the sport.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] In addition to its regional activities, BCSA has also participated in international blind cricket tournaments, including the T20 World Cup Cricket for the Blind.
[src:bete-ombro/blind-cricket] The South African national blind cricket team has achieved success in these competitions, reaching the semifinals of the 3rd edition of the T20 World Cup Cricket for the Blind held in India in 2022.
[src:bete-ombro/bowled] In cricket, the term **bowled** has several meanings.
[src:bete-ombro/bowled] First, it is the act of propelling the ball towards the wicket defended by a batter.
[src:bete-ombro/bowled] Second, it is a method of dismissing a batter, by hitting the wicket with a ball delivered by the bowler.
[src:bete-ombro/bowled] Third, it is used in scoring to indicate which bowler is credited with dismissing a batter, when the batter is dismissed by being bowled, leg before wicket (LBW), caught, stumped, or hit wicket.
[src:bete-ombro/bowled] This method of dismissal is covered by Law 32 (Bowled) of the *Laws of Cricket*.
[src:bete-ombro/bowled] A batter is out Bowled if their wicket is put down by a ball delivered by the bowler.
[src:bete-ombro/bowled] It is irrelevant whether the ball has touched the bat, glove, or any part of the batter before going on to put down the wicket, though it may not touch another player or an umpire before doing so.
[src:bete-ombro/bowled] Such rules mean that out Bowled is the most obvious of dismissals: almost never requiring an appeal to the umpire; a bowled batter will usually acknowledge the dismissal voluntarily.
[src:bete-ombro/bowled] If the delivered ball deflects off the bat, and bowls the batter, then the informal term is known as *played on*, *knocked on*, *chopped on*, or *dragged on*.
[src:bete-ombro/bowled] A batter cannot be bowled from a no-ball, wide or dead ball.
[src:bete-ombro/bowled] A batter is out Bowled even if he/she could be given out by another method of dismissal instead.
[src:bete-ombro/bowled] For example, if a batter edges the ball onto the stumps (such that the bails are removed) and the ball is then caught by a fielder, the batter would be given out Bowled instead of caught.
[src:bete-ombro/bowled] Out Bowled is the second most common method of dismissal after caught, accounting for 21.4% of all Test match dismissals between 1877 and 2012.
[src:bete-ombro/bowled] The bowler is credited with the wicket if the batter is bowled.
[src:bete-ombro/bowled] Muttiah Muralitharan holds the Test record for dismissing most batters (167) through the method of out Bowled.
[src:bete-ombro/bowled] For example, a scorecard may say that a batter was 'c Smith b Jones', which reads as 'caught Smith, bowled Jones', and means he was out caught by Smith, when the bowler was Jones.
[src:bete-ombro/bowled] Or it might say 'lbw b Jones', which reads as 'lbw bowled Jones', and means he was out LBW when the bowler was Jones.
